</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-36_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-38_">Every day another <span style="font-weight: bold;">6,000</span> people take on a caring responsibility, which equals over <span style="font-weight: bold;">2 million</span> people each year</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-39_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-41_">Caring falls particularly on women in their 40s, 50s and 60s</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-42_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-44_"><span style="font-weight: bold;">1 in 4</span> women aged 50-64 has caring responsibilities for older or disabled loved ones (Carers UK, 2019)</span></li></ul><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/free-coping-with-stress-at-work-elearning-course" target="_blank" data-pf-type="Button" class="sc-kfYoZR ccMiJj pf-45_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-47_"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Click here to register</span></span></a></div></div></div></div><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-48_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-49_"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-50_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-51_"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ezzafa qUTLf pf-52_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-54_">Who is a carer?</span></h2><p class="sc-lbVvki flSuVc pf-55_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-57_">A carer is anyone, including children and adults, who look after a family member, partner or friend who needs help because of their illness, frailty, disability, a mental health problem or an addiction and cannot cope without their support.<br><br>There are formal and informal carers.
<br></span></p><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/free-coping-with-stress-at-work-elearning-course" target="_blank" data-pf-type="Button" class="sc-kfYoZR ccMiJj pf-58_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-60_"><b>Click here to register</b><br></span></a></div></div></div></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-61_"></div></div></div></div></div><div data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-jffHpj jjTcTs pf-62_"><div class="sc-iNiQyp jdiWPe"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-63_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-64_"></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-65_"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-66_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-67_"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ezzafa qUTLf pf-68_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-70_">Who is a formal carer?</span></h2><p class="sc-lbVvki flSuVc pf-71_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-73_">Formal carers are those who are paid to give care. They act in an agency-client relationship and are paid for the services rendered.<br><br>They are usually trained, and there is an assessment procedure that determines the kind and amount of care that the client will receive from the carer. For example, a nurse is a formal caregiver, and a family member is an informal caregiver.<br></span></p></div></div></div><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/free-coping-with-stress-at-work-elearning-course" target="_blank" data-pf-type="Button" class="sc-kfYoZR ccMiJj pf-74_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-76_"><b>Click here to register</b><br></span></a></div></div></div></div></div><div data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-jffHpj jjTcTs pf-77_"><div class="sc-iNiQyp jdiWPe"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-78_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-79_"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-80_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-81_"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ezzafa qUTLf pf-82_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-84_">Who is an informal carer?</span></h2><p class="sc-lbVvki flSuVc pf-85_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-87_">An informal carer is usually a voluntary role and is offered by the family, neighbours or friends. The carer may be living with the care receiver and hence providing care 24 hours.<br><br>Informal carers do not receive any financial payments for the care they give and usually have some kind of employment apart from their caring duties, either part-time, full-time, or self-employed.<br></span></p></div></div></div><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/free-coping-with-stress-at-work-elearning-course" target="_blank" data-pf-type="Button" class="sc-kfYoZR ccMiJj pf-88_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-90_"><b>Click here to register</b><br></span></a></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-91_"></div></div></div></div></div><div data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-jffHpj jjTcTs pf-92_"><div class="sc-iNiQyp jdiWPe"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-93_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:6;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-94_"></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-95_"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-96_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-97_"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ezzafa qUTLf pf-98_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-100_">Increase in the number of informal carers</span></h2><p class="sc-lbVvki flSuVc pf-101_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-103_">1 in 4 adults is a carer (Carerweek.org, 2020). There are an estimated 13.6 million unpaid carers in the UK today. Most of these unpaid carers, 9.1 million, were already caring before the coronavirus outbreak. A staggering 4.5 million people have started providing unpaid care since the outbreak. This represents nearly a 50% increase in the number of unpaid carers since the crisis began. An estimated 26% of the UK adult population provides unpaid care to an older, disabled or ill relative or friend, equivalent to one in four adults (Carerweek.org, 2020).
<br><br>Numbers have fluctuated over the past decade. They peaked at 5.6 million in 2012/13 and 5.4 million in 2016/17. The 2017/18 estimate of 4.5 million carers was the lowest recorded since 2007/08 and remained constant in 2018/19 and 2019/20. In each year, around 60% of informal carers are women (House of Commons Library, 2021).
<br></span></p></div></div></div><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/free-coping-with-stress-at-work-elearning-course" target="_blank" data-pf-type="Button" class="sc-kfYoZR ccMiJj pf-104_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-106_"><b>Click here to register</b><br></span></a></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:6;--c-lg:5"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-107_"></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-108_"></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:6;--c-lg:5"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-109_"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-110_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-111_"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ezzafa qUTLf pf-112_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-114_">What are the roles and responsibilities of a carer?</span></h2><p class="sc-lbVvki flSuVc pf-115_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-117_">The roles and responsibilities of carers include:<br></span></p></div></div></div><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List" class="sc-oeezt OJJCp pf-118_"><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-119_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-121_">Monitoring individuals’ conditions by taking their temperature, pulse, respiration and weight, and possibly helping with medication
</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-122_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-124_">Carers support people with all aspects of their day to day living, including social and physical activities, personal care, mobility and meal times.
</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-125_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-127_">Support people with social and physical activities</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-128_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-130_">Booking and going with people to appointments</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-131_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-133_">Helping with personal care such as support with showering and dressing
</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-134_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-136_">Helping with personal care such as support with showering and dressing
</span></li></ul><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/free-coping-with-stress-at-work-elearning-course" target="_blank" data-pf-type="Button" class="sc-kfYoZR ccMiJj pf-137_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-139_"><b>Click here to register</b><br></span></a></div></div></div></div></div><div data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-jffHpj jjTcTs pf-140_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-iNiQyp jdiWPe"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-141_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-142_"></div></div></div></div></div><div data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-jffHpj jjTcTs pf-143_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-iNiQyp jdiWPe"><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-144_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-145_"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/pf-99f65414--supportingofthefriend9VRBNULjpg.png?v=1623421982" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/pf-99f65414--supportingofthefriend9VRBNULjpg.png?v=1623421982 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/pf-99f65414--supportingofthefriend9VRBNULjpg_500x.png?v=1623421982 320w" data-pf-type="Image" class="sc-jJMGnK laKGqb pf-146_"/></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-147_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ezzafa qUTLf pf-148_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-150_">What are the challenges faced by carers?</span></h3><p class="sc-lbVvki flSuVc pf-151_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-153_">The caregivers often face common challenges that leave them overwhelmed, anxious and intimidated by their duties. Some of these challenges a family caregiver faces are:<br></span></p><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List" class="sc-oeezt OJJCp pf-154_"><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-155_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-157_">Financial problems: Many carers give up aspects of their lives to dedicate their time to support sick or disabled relatives. The financial implications of giving up work to care for them also has a huge impact.&nbsp;</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-158_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-160_">Mental health problems: The isolation and stress of caring can also cause mental health problems, and getting into debt exacerbates this. Nearly 75% said they had suffered mental health problems, with that figure rising when the carers had been in debt.
</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-161_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-163_">Depression: most carers suffer from depression</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-164_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-166_">Anger: Carers may feel angry about many aspects of their situation - the unfairness, the responsibilities and the change in lifestyle.</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hhIiOg iwisNA pf-167_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-169_">Physical strain: Many caregivers complain of backache as they lift their patients to help them with their day to day tasks.</span></li></ul><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/free-coping-with-stress-at-work-elearning-course" target="_blank" data-pf-type="Button" class="sc-kfYoZR ccMiJj pf-170_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-172_"><b>Click here to register</b><br></span></a></div></div></div><div class="sc-dlMDgC kpPvTx pf-173_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-hTRkXV enlJuL pf-174_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ezzafa qUTLf pf-175_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jUfyBS eSyZIh pf-177_">Where can carers find support?
